<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-696-117  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 696 117.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Federal Computer Week  Dec 3 1990 v4 n40 p26(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Off-the-shelf software tracks satellites.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Mercier, Ann M.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Off-the-shelf software is being used to track and analyzesatellite systems by such government agencies as the NationalSecurity Agency, the Central Intelligence Agency and the US SpaceCommand.andP;  An interactive, two-dimensional graphics packagedeveloped by Analytical Graphics (King of Prussia, PA), calledSatellite Tool Kit, allows mission planners, operations staff andsatellite system engineers analyze and display data aboutaircraft, satellite, ship and terrestrial vehicle paths.andP;  Thepackage is priced at $4,995 per license.andP;  IBM has designed ademonstration package called Astronautical Simulation andInteractive Graphical Trajectory (AstroSight), which will show thecapabilities of the company's RISC System/6000 workstation.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   Analytical Graphics (Products).andO;Topic:     SatellitesTracking SystemsSoftware PackagesGovernment AgencyGraphics SoftwareCost.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>